  "diary": "Woke to rain drumming on the roof—that grey, relentless Tuesday kind. Coffee tasted better than usual, maybe because I knew the commute would be rough. SR-520 was a mess, but I'd built in extra time, so I wasn't stressed. The office was the usual controlled chaos of tax season. Back-to-back client meetings, spreadsheets blurring together. Grabbed lunch under the awning of that deli on Cherry, watching the rain sheet down. The afternoon felt long, but I powered through reconciliations and follow-ups. By the time I left, the rain had stopped and the drive home was almost peaceful. Made a simple pasta, nothing fancy. Then the pottery studio—just me, the wheel, and clay. There's something about centering it that quiets everything else. My hands remembered the motion even after weeks away. Felt good to make something shapeless into something whole.",
  "thought_process": "The weather and traffic closure could've derailed me, but I chose to see them as givens rather than obstacles—built buffer time, left early. Tax season keeps me desk-bound and mentally rigid, so I was conscious of that tension all day. Lunch was functional, but dinner and pottery were intentional counterbalances. I've learned that after hours of client handholding and number-crunching, I need to do something tactile and aimless. The pottery isn't about productivity; it's about remembering I'm more than spreadsheets. The rain lifting by evening felt symbolic somehow—like permission to exhale. My mood started guarded but gradually loosened as the day moved from obligation to autonomy.",
